The outcome variable is ordinal. We, therefore, reorder the ranking levels from least to best. This is critical, and must be done!

df_Mktrait$MktraitRANK <- ordered(df_Mktrait$MktraitRANK,
  levels = c("strongly_disagree", "disagree", "not_sure", "agree", "strongly_agree"))
levels(df_Mktrait$MktraitRANK) # check the levels to confirm reordering
## [1] "strongly_disagree" "disagree"          "not_sure"         
## [4] "agree"             "strongly_agree"

Because the predictor variables are categorical, R generates dummy variables with base and indicator variables. Let’s remind ourselves of how R handles dummy variables. R selects the first factor in alphabetical order as the base category, and the remaining categories as indicator variables. For Mktrait, R selects the DR as the base, and for SCseg R selects SA as the base.

Once the data structure is checked we are ready to apply proportional odds logit models

Fit the Proportional Odds Logistic Regression Models

The polr function from the MASS package is used for proportional odds regression.

We are interested to know the interaction effect of Pddtrait and SCseg so we first go through a restricted modelling process. We compare three models to see which one is the best using likelihood ratios tests.

library(MASS)

POLR Model #1

fit001 <- polr(MktraitRANK ~ Mktrait,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Mktrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

POLR Model #2

fit002 <- polr(MktraitRANK ~ Mktrait + SCseg,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Mktrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

POLR Model #3

fit003 <- polr(MktraitRANK ~ Mktrait + SCseg + Mktrait:SCseg,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Mktrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

Perform likelihood ratio tests of Models 1-3

anova(fit001, fit002, fit003)

There is marginal significance between Model 2 and 3, hence, we select Model #3 which has the interaction term.

Another model selection approach would be to specify the general model and conduct a stepwise backward and forward modelling. This is automated in R with the step function. Below, the step function also selects the model with interaction between Mktrait and SCseg as the best model. We are double sure about the selected model.

step(fit003, test = "Chisq", direction = "both") # perform a forward and backward stepwise model, and perform likelihood ratio test at each step

It is easier to interpret the model with p-values instead of the t-values. Calculate the p-values and append to the coefficients table

# get coefficients (it's in matrix form)
coefficients <- summary(fit003)$coefficients
# calculate p-values
p_value <- (1 - pnorm(abs(coefficients[ ,"t value"]), 0, 1))*2
# bind back to coefficients
(coefficients <- cbind(coefficients, p_value))

Odds ratios are very useful for explaining the parameter estimates. We calculate the odds ratios and further calculate a less biased version recommended for categorical predictors (Baker, 2006).

# calculate odds ratios
odds_ratio <- exp(coefficients[ ,"Value"]) #this is biased for categorical/dummy variables and tends to slightly overstate the effect
# for reduced bias odds ratios for dummy variables, use
odds_ratio_cat <- exp((coefficients[ ,"Value"])-((((coefficients[ ,"Std. Error"])^2)*(coefficients[ ,"Value"]))/2))
# combine with coefficient and p_value
(coefficients <- cbind(
  coefficients[ ,c("Value", "Std. Error", "p_value")],
  odds_ratio, odds_ratio_cat
))

Dealing with Interaction Term

The estimates for the interaction term in the model summary are tricky!! Needs a bit of extra work to explain them. To make life easier, because there is enough evidence of a significant “SCseg” and “Mktrait” interactions (at the 10% level), “SCseg” and “Mktrait” are bound to form a single categorical variable “SCseg|Mktrait” with 12 levels. One combination is selected as the reference level.

We concatenate the variables in the interaction term and refit the model. We go through all the procedures to include p-values, odds ratios, model fit parameters, etc.

Model #4 (with concateated iteraction term)

#concatenate string/factor variables and store as a new column
df_Mktrait$SCsegTrait <- as.factor(paste(df_Mktrait$SCseg, df_Mktrait$Mktrait, sep = "|")) #combining SCseg and Mktrait 
# fit new model
fit004 <- polr(MktraitRANK ~ SCsegTrait,
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Mktrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

# get coefficients (it's in matrix form)
coefficients <- summary(fit004)$coefficients
# calculate p-values
p_value <- (1 - pnorm(abs(coefficients[ ,"t value"]), 0, 1))*2
# bind back to coefficients
coefficients <- cbind(coefficients, p_value)
# calculate odds ratios
odds_ratio <- exp(coefficients[ ,"Value"]) #this is biased for categorical/dummy variables and tends to slightly overstate the effect
# for reduced bias odds ratios for dummy variables, use
odds_ratio_cat <- exp((coefficients[ ,"Value"])-((((coefficients[ ,"Std. Error"])^2)*(coefficients[ ,"Value"]))/2))
# combine with coefficient and p_value
(coefficients <- cbind(
  coefficients[ ,c("Value", "Std. Error", "p_value")],
  odds_ratio, odds_ratio_cat
))

Predict mean categorical rank outcomes for specific traits of in each state

Now, instead of cumulative probablities of the ranking levels as demostrated above, we can predict the mean categorical outcomes using the best POLR model. For example we can use the model to generate the mean rank likely to be assigned the production trait, disease resistance by SA producers. Below is a demostration of how to do these predictions for all twelvee combinations of SCseg*Mktrait interactions.

# Get levels of each categorical predictor using the terms in the model
LEVELS1 <- levels(df_MktraitRANKselect$Mktrait)
LEVELS2 <- levels(df_MktraitRANKselect$SCseg)
# Create a data.frame to store the predictions
df_predRANKS <- data.frame(
  Mktrait   = rep(LEVELS1, length(LEVELS2)),
  SCseg = rep(LEVELS2, each=length(LEVELS1))
)
# Add the predictions
df_predRANKS$predRANKS <- predict(model_best, df_predRANKS)

library(Hmisc)

sf <- function(y) {
  c('Y>=1' = qlogis(mean(y >= 1)),
    'Y>=2' = qlogis(mean(y >= 2)),
    'Y>=3' = qlogis(mean(y >= 3)),
    'Y>=4' = qlogis(mean(y >= 4)),
    'Y>=5' = qlogis(mean(y >= 5)))
}
